            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  For any poset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, it generates a free distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2[I]]]></fr:tex>. When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is finite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2[I]]]></fr:tex> is a Heyting algebra, but it will never be Boolean expect when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is empty. The spectrum
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} 2[I] \cong  \mathbf {Pos}(I,2) \cong  \mathcal {U}(I), ]]></fr:tex>
  is the upward closed subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>. Since free distributive lattices are always <fr:link href="/idem-comm-75C1/" title="Local distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-75C1/" display-uri="idem-comm-75C1" type="local">local</fr:link> and <fr:link href="/idem-comm-487K/" title="Integral distributive lattices" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-487K/" display-uri="idem-comm-487K" type="local">integral</fr:link>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} 2[I]]]></fr:tex> has both a root <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> and a focal point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
